{{Infobox spaceflight | name = Ariel 1 | image = Thor Delta with Ariel 1 (Apr. 26, 1962).jpg | image_caption = Launch of Ariel 1 on a Thor-Delta rocket
| mission_type = Ionospheric | operator = [[Science and Engineering Research Council|SERC]]{{\}}[[NASA]]<ref>[http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/masterCatalog.do?sc=1962-015A Ariel 1] NSSDC Master Catalog. Retrieved 20 January 2015.</ref> | website = | Harvard_designation = 1962 Omicron 1 | SATCAT = 285 | mission_duration =
| spacecraft_bus = | manufacturer = [[Goddard Space Flight Center]] | dry_mass = | launch_mass = {{convert|62|kg}} | power =
| launch_date = {{start-date|26 April 1962, 18:00:16|timezone=yes}}&nbsp;UTC | launch_rocket = [[Thor-Delta|Thor DM-19 Delta]] | launch_site = [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]] [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station Space Launch Complex 17|LC-17A]] | launch_contractor =
| disposal_type = | deactivated = | last_contact = <!-- {{end-date|[insert date here]}} --> | decay_date = 24 May 1976
| orbit_epoch = 14 June 1962<ref name="satcat">{{cite web|url=http://planet4589.org/space/log/satcat.txt|title=Satellite Catalog|first=Jonathan|last=McDowell|work=Jonathan's Space Page|accessdate=6 December 2013}}</ref> | orbit_reference = [[geocentric orbit|Geocentric]] | orbit_regime = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]] | excentricity = 0.0561326957 | orbit_periapsis = {{convert|397|km|mi}} | orbit_apoapsis = {{convert|1202|km|mi}} | orbit_inclination = 53.8&nbsp;degrees | orbit_period = 100.86&nbsp;minutes | apsis = gee }} '''Ariel 1''' (also known as '''UK-1''' and '''S-55'''), was the first [[United Kingdom|British]] [[satellite]], and the first satellite in the [[Ariel programme]]. Its launch in 1962 made the United Kingdom the third country to operate a satellite, after the [[Soviet Union]] and the [[United States]]. It was constructed in both the UK and the [[United States]] by [[NASA Goddard Space Flight Center]] and [[Science and Engineering Research Council|SERC]], under an agreement reached as the result of political discussions in 1959 and 1960.
== Development == [[File:Ariel 1 satellite, London Science Museum.JPG|thumb|left|Ariel 1 satellite, London Science Museum]] In late 1959, the [[Science and Engineering Research Council]] proposed the development of Ariel 1 to NASA, following an offer made by the United States at a meeting of the [[Committee on Space Research]] to provide assistance to other countries with the development and launch of scientific spacecraft. By early the following year the two countries had decided upon terms for the programme's scope and which organisations would be responsible for which parts of the programme.
Prime Minister [[Harold Macmillan]] named the satellite after [[Ariel (Shakespeare character)|the sprite in Shakespeare's ''The Tempest'']].<ref name="ley196406" >{{Cite magazine |last=Ley |first=Willy |date=June 1964 |title=Anyone Else for Space? |department=For Your Information |url=https://archive.org/stream/Galaxy_v22n05_1964-06_modified#page/n69/mode/2up |magazine=Galaxy Science Fiction |pages=110-128 }}</ref> Construction occurred at the [[Goddard Space Flight Center]]. SERC provided the experiments, conducted operations, and later analysed and interpreted the results. Six experiments were carried aboard the satellite. Five of these examined the relationship between two types of [[solar radiation]] and changes in the Earth's [[ionosphere]]. They took advantage of techniques developed in the [[Skylark (rocket)|Skylark]] programme.
{{clear left}} == Launch, operation, orbit == [[File:19620426 Delta 9-Ariel 1 LC-17A.jpg|thumb|left|US Delta 9 rocket with UK first satellite Ariel 1, 26 April 1962]] Ariel 1, the first satellite from a nation besides the United States or the Soviet Union,<ref name="ley196712" >{{Cite magazine |last=Ley |first=Willy |date=December 1967 |title=Astronautics International |department=For Your Information |url=https://archive.org/stream/Galaxy_v26n02_1967-12_modified#page/n37/mode/2up |magazine=Galaxy Science Fiction |pages=110-120 }}</ref> was launched aboard an American [[Thor-Delta]] rocket from [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station Launch Complex 17|Launch Complex 17A]] at the [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station]], at 18:00:16 GMT on 26 April 1962. Ariel 1 was among several satellites inadvertently damaged or destroyed by the [[Starfish Prime]] [[high-altitude nuclear explosion|high-altitude nuclear test]] on July 9, 1962, and subsequent [[List of artificial radiation belts|radiation belt]]. It [[orbital decay|decayed]] from orbit on 24 April 1976.
