{{Infobox Bilateral relations|Georgian–Turkish|Georgia|Turkey|map=Georgia Turkey locator.svg}}

'''Georgian–Turkish relations''' are foreign relations between [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] and [[Turkey]]. After the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]], Turkey recognized the independence of Georgia on 16 December 1991.<ref name="mfa.gov.tr Georgia" /> The formal Protocol on the Establishment of Diplomatic Relations between the two countries was signed on 21 May 1992.<ref name="mfa.gov.tr Georgia">[http://www.mfa.gov.tr/turkey_s-political-relations-with-georgia.en.mfa Turkey´s Political Relations With Georgia] Republic of Turkey Ministry of Foreign Affairs</ref> A [[free trade agreement]] is currently in force.<ref name="mfa.gov.tr Georgia" /> 
Georgia has an embassy in [[Ankara]],<ref>[http://embassy.mfa.gov.ge/index.php?lang_id=ENG&sec_id=117&lang_id=ENG Georgian Embassy in Ankara]  [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Georgia]]</ref> and two [[consulate]]s–general in [[Istanbul]] and [[Trabzon]]. Turkey has an embassy in [[Tbilisi]],<ref>[http://turkey.visahq.com/embassy/Georgia/ Turkish Embassy in Tbilisi]</ref> and a consulate–general in [[Batumi]]. Both countries are full members of the [[Council of Europe]], the [[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]], the [[BLACKSEAFOR]] (Black Sea Naval Co-operation Task Group), the [[Organization of the Black Sea Economic Cooperation]] and the [[World Trade Organization]]. Turkey is already a member of [[NATO]], while [[Georgia and NATO|Georgia is a candidate]].

